Definition 8.1. A geometric theory $\mathbb{T}$ is interpretable in a geometric theory $\mathbb{S}$ if there is a geometric functor $I:\mathscr{C}_{\mathbb{T}}\rightarrow\mathscr{C}_{\mathbb{S}}$ between the respective syntactic categories. If $I$ is also a categorical equivalence we say that $\mathbb{T}$ and $\mathbb{S}$ are bi-interpretable.
Definition 3.1. An MV-algebra is a structure $\mathcal{A}=(A,\oplus,\neg,0)$, where $\oplus$ is a binary relation symbol, $\neg$ is a unary relation symbol and $0$ is a constant, satisfying the following axioms: (1) $(x\oplus y)\oplus z=x\oplus(y\oplus z)$; (2) $x\oplus y=y\oplus x$; (3) $x\oplus 0=x$; (4) $\neg\neg x=x$; (5) $x\oplus\neg 0=\neg 0$; (6) $\neg(\neg x\oplus y)\oplus y=\neg(\neg y\oplus x)\oplus x$.
Definition 4.1. (cf. [8]) A lattice-orderd abelian group ($\ell$-group, for brevity) is a structure $\mathcal{G}=(G,+,-,\leq,0)$ such that $(G,+,-,0)$ is an abelian group, $(G,\leq)$ is a lattice-ordered set and the following translation invariance property holds: $\text{for any }x,y,z\in G\qquad x\leq y\text{ implies }x+z\leq y+z.$
Definition 2.10. [22] Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory. A model $\mathcal{M}$ of $\mathbb{T}$ in ${\bf Set}$ is finitely presentable if the representable functor $Hom(\mathcal{M},-):\mathbb{T}$-mod$({\bf Set})\rightarrow{\bf Set}$ preserves filtered colimits.
Definition 3.5. An MV-algebra $\mathcal{A}=(A,\oplus,\neg,0)$ is said to be perfect if $\mathcal{A}$ is non-trivial (i.e., $A\neq\{0\}$ or equivalently $1\neq 0$) and $A=Rad(\mathcal{A})\cup\neg Rad(\mathcal{A})$, where $\neg Rad(\mathcal{A})=\{x\in A\mid\neg x\in Rad(\mathcal{A})\}$.
Definition 2.11. [14] Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory over a one-sorted signature $\Sigma$ and $\phi(\vec{x})=\phi(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$ be a geometric formula over $\Sigma$. We say that a $\mathbb{T}$-model $\mathcal{M}$ in ${\bf Set}$ is finitely presented by $\phi(\vec{x})$ (or that $\phi(\vec{x})$ presents $\mathcal{M}$) if there exists a string of elements $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\in\mathcal{M}^{n}$, called generators of $\mathcal{M}$, such that for any $\mathbb{T}$-model $\mathcal{N}$ in ${\bf Set}$ and any string of elements $(b_{1},\dots,b_{n})\in[[\vec{x}.\phi]]_{\mathcal{N}}$, there exists a unique arrow $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathcal{N}$ in $\mathbb{T}$-mod$({\bf Set})$ such that $f(a_{i})=b_{i}$ for $i=1,\dots,n$.
Definition 2.6. A geometric theory is a theory over a first-order signature $\Sigma$ whose axioms can be presented in the sequent form $(\phi\vdash_{\vec{x}}\psi)$ (intuitively meaning ‘$\phi$ entails $\psi$ in the context $\vec{x}$, i.e. for any values of the variables in $\vec{x}$’), where $\phi$ and $\psi$ are geometric formulas, that is formulas with a finite number of free variables, all of which occurring in the context $\vec{x}$, built up from atomic formulas over $\Sigma$ by only using finitary conjunctions, infinitary disjunctions and existential quantifications.
Definition 2.1. A Grothendieck topology on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a function $J$ which assigns to each object $c\in\mathscr{C}$ a collection $J(c)$ of sieves on $c$ in such a way (i) the maximal sieve $\{f\mid cod(f)=c\}$ is in $J(c)$; (ii) (stability axiom) if $S\in J(c)$, then $h^{*}(S)\in J(d)$ for any morphism $h:d\rightarrow c$, where with the symbol $h^{*}(S)$ we mean the sieve whose morphisms are the pullbaks along $h$ of the morphisms in $S$; (iii) (transitivity axiom) if $S\in J(c)$ and $R$ is a sieve on $c$ such that $h^{*}(R)\in J(d)$ for all $h:d\rightarrow c$ in $S$, then $R\in J(c)$.
Definition 2.4. Given a site $(\mathscr{C},J)$, and a set $I$ of objects of $\mathscr{C}$. If for any arrow $f:a\to b$ in $\mathscr{C}$, $b\in I$ implies $a\in I$, we say that $I$ is an ideal. If further for any $J$-covering sieve $S$ on an object $c$ of $\mathscr{C}$, if $dom(f)\in I$ for all $f\in S$ then $c\in I$, we say that $I$ is a $J$-ideal.
Definition 2.7. A Grothendieck topos $\mathscr{E}$ classifies a geometric theory $\mathbb{T}$ if there exists a categorical equivalence between the category of models of $\mathbb{T}$ in an arbitrary Grothendieck topos $\mathscr{F}$ and the category of geometric morphisms from $\mathscr{F}$ to $\mathscr{E}$, naturally in $\mathscr{F}$ or, in other words, if there exists a model $U$ of $\mathbb{T}$ in $\mathscr{E}$, called ‘the’ universal model of $\mathbb{T}$ in $\mathscr{E}$, such that any other model of $\mathbb{T}$ in a topos $\mathscr{F}$ is isomorphic to $f^{\ast}(U)$ for a unique (up to isomorphism) geometric morphism $\mathscr{F}\to\mathscr{E}$.
Definition 2.12. Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory over a signature $\Sigma$ and $\phi(\vec{x})$ a geometric formula-in-context over $\Sigma$. Then $\phi(\vec{x})$ is said to be $\mathbb{T}$-irreducible if for any family $\{\theta_{i}\mid i\in I\}$ of $\mathbb{T}$-provably functional geometric formulas $\{\vec{x_{i}},\vec{x}.\theta_{i}\}$ from $\{\vec{x_{i}}.\phi_{i}\}$ to $\{\vec{x}.\phi\}$ such that $\phi\vdash_{\vec{x}}\mathbin{\mathop{\textrm{\huge$\vee$}}\limits_{i\in I}}(% \exists\vec{x_{i}})\theta_{i}$ is provable in $\mathbb{T}$, there exist $i\in I$ and a $\mathbb{T}$-provably functional geometric formula $\{\vec{x},\vec{x_{i}}.\theta^{\prime}\}$ from $\{\vec{x}.\phi\}$ to $\{\vec{x_{i}}.\phi_{i}\}$ such that $\phi\vdash_{\vec{x}}(\exists\vec{x_{i}})(\theta^{\prime}\wedge\theta_{i})$ is provable in $\mathbb{T}$.
Definition 2.8. Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory over a signature $\Sigma$. The geometric syntactic category $\mathscr{C}_{\mathbb{T}}$ of $\mathbb{T}$ has as objects the geometric formulas-in-context $\{\vec{x}.\phi\}$ over $\Sigma$ and as arrows from $\{\vec{x}.\phi\}$ to $\{\vec{y}.\psi\}$ the $\mathbb{T}$-provable equivalence classes $[\theta]$ of geometric formulas $\theta(\vec{x},\vec{y})$, where $\vec{x}$ and $\vec{y}$ are disjoint contexts, which are $\mathbb{T}$-provably functional from $\{\vec{x}.\phi\}$ to $\{\vec{y}.\psi\}$ in the sense that the sequents - $(\theta\vdash_{\vec{x},\vec{y}}(\phi\wedge\psi))$ - $(\theta\wedge\theta[\vec{z}/\vec{y}]\vdash_{\vec{x},\vec{y},\vec{z}}(\vec{z}=% \vec{y}))$ - $(\phi\vdash_{\vec{x}}(\exists\vec{y})\theta)$ are provable in $\mathbb{T}$.
Definition 2.3. [24, section C2.1] A sieve $R$ on an object $U$ of $\mathscr{C}$ is called effective-epimorphic if it forms a colimit cone under the diagram consisting of the domains of all morphisms in $R$ and all the morphisms over $U$. A Grothendieck topology is said to be subcanonical if all its covering sieves are effective-epimorphic.
Definition 2.2. Let $(\mathscr{C},J)$ be a site. (a) A presheaf on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a functor $P:\mathscr{C}^{\textrm{op}}\to{\bf Set}$1This is the category whose objects are sets and whose morphisms are functions between sets.. (b) A sheaf on $(\mathscr{C},J)$ is a presheaf $P:\mathscr{C}^{\textrm{op}}\to{\bf Set}$ on $\mathscr{C}$ such that for every $J$-covering sieve $S\in J(c)$ and every family $\{x_{f}\in P({\rm dom}(f))\mid f\in S\}$ such that $P(g)(x_{f})=x_{f\circ g}$ for any $f\in S$ and any arrow $g$ in $\mathscr{C}$ composable with $g$ there exists a unique element $x\in P(c)$ such that $x_{f}=P(f)(x)$ for all $f\in S$. (c) The category ${\bf Sh}(\mathscr{C},J)$ of sheaves on the site $(\mathscr{C},J)$ has as objects the sheaves on $(\mathscr{C},J)$ and as arrows the natural transformations between them, regarded as functors $\mathscr{C}^{\textrm{op}}\to{\bf Set}$. (d) A Grothendieck topos is a category equivalent to a category ${\bf Sh}(\mathscr{C},J)$ of sheaves on a site.
Definition 2.5. [24, Definition C2.2.18] A Grothendieck topology $J$ on a small category $\mathscr{C}$ is said to be rigid if for every object $c$ of $\mathscr{C}$, the set of arrows from $J$-irreducible objects of $\mathscr{C}$ (i.e., the objects of $\mathscr{C}$ on which the only $J$-covering sieves are the maximal ones) generates a $J$-covering sieve.
Definition 4.0.1. A $\mathcal{B}_{w}$-module $\mathcal{M}$ is perfect if it lies in the smallest thick subcategory classically generated by the $\mathcal{B}_{w}\otimes_{\mathcal{O}_{S}}\mathcal{L}$. The category $\operatorname{D}_{\operatorname{pe}}(\operatorname{Mod}_{\operatorname{\mathbb% {Z}}}\mathcal{B}_{w})$ is the full subcategory of perfect objects in $\operatorname{D}(\operatorname{Mod}_{\operatorname{\mathbb{Z}}}\mathcal{B}_{w})$.
Definition 5.0.2. We denote the differential induced by $\operatorname{d}_{Koszul}$ by $\partial:\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{B}$ and differential of $\mathcal{B}_{w}$ by $\overline{\partial}$ in keeping with standing notation for homological perturbation.
Definition 2.0.6. An elementary wall-crossing, $(\mathfrak{K}^{+},\mathfrak{K}^{-})$, is a pair of elementary HKKN stratifications, $\displaystyle Q=$ $\displaystyle Q_{\lambda}\sqcup S_{\lambda},$ $\displaystyle Q=$ $\displaystyle Q_{-\lambda}\sqcup S_{-\lambda},$ such that $Z^{0}_{\lambda}=Z^{0}_{-\lambda}$. We often let $Q_{+}:=Q_{\lambda}$ and $Q_{-}:=Q_{-\lambda}$.
Definition 2.0.2. A coherent factorization, or simply a factorization, of a gauged LG model, $([Q/G],w)$, consists of a pair of coherent $G$-equivariant sheaves, $\mathcal{E}^{-1}$ and $\mathcal{E}^{0}$, and a pair of $G$-equivariant $\mathcal{O}_{Q}$-module homomorphisms, $\displaystyle\phi^{-1}_{\mathcal{E}}$ $\displaystyle:\mathcal{E}^{0}(-1)\to\mathcal{E}^{-1}$ $\displaystyle\phi^{0}_{\mathcal{E}}$ $\displaystyle:\mathcal{E}^{-1}\to\mathcal{E}^{0}$ such that the compositions, $\phi^{0}_{\mathcal{E}}\circ\phi^{-1}_{\mathcal{E}}:\mathcal{E}_{0}(-1)\to% \mathcal{E}^{0}$ and $\phi^{-1}_{\mathcal{E}}(1)\circ\phi_{\mathcal{E}}^{0}:\mathcal{E}^{-1}\to% \mathcal{E}^{-1}(1)$, are multiplication by $w$. We shall often simply denote the factorization $(\mathcal{E}^{-1},\mathcal{E}^{0},\phi_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1},\phi_{\mathcal{E}}^{% 0})$ by $\mathcal{E}$. The coherent $G$-equivariant sheaves, $\mathcal{E}^{0}$ and $\mathcal{E}^{-1}$, are called the components of the factorization, $\mathcal{E}$. A morphism of factorizations, $g:\mathcal{E}\to\mathcal{F}$, is a pair of morphisms $(g^{-1},g^{0})$ that commute with $\phi^{i}_{\mathcal{E}}$ and $\phi^{i}_{\mathcal{F}}$. Let $\operatorname{coh}([Q/G],w)$ be the Abelian category of factorizations with coherent components.
Definition 2.0.4. Assume $Q$ is a smooth variety with a $G$-action. An elementary HKKN stratification of $Q$ is a disjoint union $\mathfrak{K}:Q=Q_{\lambda}\sqcup S_{\lambda},$ obtained from the choice of a one-parameter subgroup $\lambda:\mathbb{G}_{m}\to G$, together with the choice of a connected component, denoted $Z_{\lambda}^{0}$, of the fixed locus of $\lambda$ such that • $S_{\lambda}$ is closed in $X$. • The morphism, $\displaystyle\tau_{\lambda}:[(G\times Z_{\lambda})/P(\lambda)]$ $\displaystyle\to S_{\lambda}$ $\displaystyle(g,z)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto g\cdot z$ is an isomorphism where $p\in P(\lambda)$ acts by $(p,(g,z))\mapsto(gp^{-1},p\cdot z).$
Definition 5.1.1. For a sheaf of graded $A_{\infty}$ algebras $\mathcal{A}$, let $\operatorname{D}_{\operatorname{pe}}(\operatorname{Mod}_{\infty,\operatorname{% \mathbb{Z}}}{\mathcal{A}})$ be the smallest thick triangulated subcategory of the derived category of strictly unital graded $A_{\infty}$ $\mathcal{A}$-modules containing all modules of the form $\mathcal{A}\otimes_{\mathcal{O}_{S}}\mathcal{L}$ for graded invertible sheaves $\mathcal{L}$ on $S$. If we wish to emphasize the underlying variety, we will also denote this category by $\operatorname{D}_{\operatorname{pe}}(\operatorname{Mod}_{\infty,\operatorname{% \mathbb{Z}}}{(S,\mathcal{A})})$.
Definition 2.0.3. A factorization, $\mathcal{A}$, is called totally acyclic if it lies in the smallest thick subcategory of $K(\operatorname{coh}[Q/G],w)$ containing all totalizations [BDFIK12, Definition 2.10] of short exact sequences from $\operatorname{coh}([Q/G],w)$. We let $\operatorname{acycl}([Q/G],w)$ denote the thick subcategory of $K(\operatorname{coh}[Q/G],w)$ consisting of totally acyclic factorizations. The absolute derived category of factorizations, or the derived category, of the LG model $([Q/G],w)$, is the Verdier quotient, $\operatorname{D}(\operatorname{coh}[Q/G],w):=K(\operatorname{coh}[Q/G],w)/% \operatorname{acycl}([Q/G],w).$ Abusing terminology, we say that $\mathcal{E}$ and $\mathcal{F}$ are quasi-isomorphic factorizations if they are isomorphic in the absolute derived category.
Definition 2.0.5. The weight of the stratum $S_{\lambda}$ is the $\lambda$-weight of $\omega_{S_{\lambda}/Q}|_{Z_{\lambda}^{0}}$. It is denoted by $t(\mathfrak{K})$.
Definition 2.0.1. A gauged Landau-Ginzburg model, or gauged LG model, is the quadruple, $(Q,G,\mathcal{L},w)$, with $Q$, $G$, $\mathcal{L}$, and $w$ as above. We shall commonly denote a gauged LG model by the pair $([Q/G],w)$.
Definition 5.0.3. [KS01, IK04] A ribbon tree is a tree $T$ with a collection of vertices, a collection of semi-infinite edges $\{e_{0},\ldots,e_{n}\}$ and a collection of finite edges such that: (a) Each semi-infinite edge is incident to a single vertex. (b) Each finite edge is incident to exactly two vertices. (c) The planar structure of $T$ has the semi-infinite edges $e_{0},\ldots,e_{n}$ arranged in clockwise order. The edge $e_{0}$ is called the root and $e_{1},\ldots,e_{n}$ are called the leaves.
Definition 4.0.2. An additive category, $\mathcal{A}$, is idempotent complete if for every morphism $e:A\to A$ with $e^{2}=e$ there is a splitting $A\cong\operatorname{ker}(e)\oplus\operatorname{im}(e).$
Definition 2.11. Let $\mathcal{S}\in\textsc{Pres}_{\otimes,\mathbb{K}}$, and $\mathcal{C}\in\textsc{Pres}_{\mathbb{K}}$ an $\mathcal{S}$-module in the sense of Definition 2.8. An object $M\in\mathcal{C}$ is tiny over $\mathcal{S}$ if the enriched hom functor $\hom(M,-)_{\mathcal{S}}:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{S}$ is cocontinuous. We say that $\mathcal{C}$ is tinily-spanned over $\mathcal{S}$ if every object is an $\mathcal{S}$-weighted colimit of tiny-over-$\mathcal{S}$ objects.
Definition 4.1. An $\mathcal{I}$-indexed pro-object (or just pro-object, when $\mathcal{I}$ is understood) in a category $\mathcal{T}$ is a functor $\mathcal{I}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathcal{T}$. An $\mathcal{I}$-indexed pro-algebra (or just pro-algebra) is an $\mathcal{I}$-indexed pro-object in $\mathbb{K}$-algebras. An acceptable ($\mathcal{I}$-indexed) pro-algebra is a pro-algebra whose indexing poset $\mathcal{I}$ has countable cofinality (i.e. it has a countable cofinal subset), and for which the transition maps $A_{j}\to A_{i}$ for $i\leq j$ are onto.
Definition 2.1. For a cardinal $\lambda$ (possibly finite), a partially ordered set $\mathcal{I}$ is $\lambda$-directed if any subset of $\mathcal{I}$ of cardinality strictly less than $\lambda$ has an upper bound. A $\lambda$-directed colimit is a colimit indexed by a $\lambda$-directed partially ordered set. An object $X$ in a category $\mathcal{C}$ is $\lambda$-little if $\hom(X,-)$ commutes with $\lambda$-directed colimits, and little if it is $\lambda$-little for some $\lambda$. A colimit is $\lambda$-small if its indexing diagram has strictly fewer than $\lambda$ arrows (including identity arrows). A set of objects $\Gamma$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is spanning if every object of $\mathcal{C}$ is a colimit of a diagram with objects in $\Gamma$. A $\mathbb{K}$-linear category $\mathcal{C}$ is locally presentable if it is cocomplete (i.e. has all colimits) and admits a spanning set consisting entirely of little objects. We may imagine $\mathcal{C}$ as a “categorified vector space over $\mathbb{K}$.” Locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear categories are the objects of a bicategory $\textsc{Pres}_{\mathbb{K}}$ whose 1-morphisms are cocontinuous $\mathbb{K}$-linear functors and whose 2-morphisms are natural transformations. The special adjoint functor theorem implies that every cocontinuous functor $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ with $\mathcal{C}$ locally presentable has a right adjoint (in the bicategory of all functors).
Definition 4.9. An ind-scheme $X=\varinjlim_{i\in I}X_{i}$ is tensorial if for every commutative algebra $B$ the canonical functor $\varinjlim_{i}\hom\bigl{(}\operatorname{Spec}(B),X_{i}\bigr{)}=\hom\bigl{(}% \operatorname{Spec}(B),X\bigr{)}\to\operatorname{\textsc{Hom}}_{\otimes}\bigl{% (}\operatorname{\textsc{Qcoh}}(X),\mathcal{M}_{B}\bigr{)},\quad f\mapsto f^{*}$ is an equivalence of categories. Hence, given an acceptable commutative pro-algebra $\{A_{i}\}_{i\in\mathcal{I}^{\mathrm{op}}}$, the corresponding affine ind-scheme $\varinjlim\operatorname{Spec}(A_{i})$ is tensorial if for every commutative algebra $B$ the canonical functor $\varinjlim_{i}\hom\bigl{(}A_{i},B\bigr{)}\to\operatorname{\textsc{Hom}}_{% \otimes}\Bigr{(}\varprojlim_{i}\mathcal{M}_{A_{i}},\mathcal{M}_{B}\Bigl{)}$ is an equivalence of categories.
Definition 1.1. A locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear category $\mathcal{C}$ is called dualizable if the canonical functor $\mathcal{C}\boxtimes\mathcal{C}^{*}\to\operatorname{\textsc{End}}(\mathcal{C})$ is an equivalence. A locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear category $\mathcal{C}$ is called reflexive if the canonical functor $\mathcal{C}\to(\mathcal{C}^{*})^{*}$ is an equivalence.
Definition 2.8. We say that $\mathcal{S}\in\textsc{Pres}_{\mathbb{K}}$ is a symmetric monoidal locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear category if it is symmetric monoidal as a category and the monoidal structure $\otimes:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$ is cocontinuous and $\mathbb{K}$-linear in each variable, so that it extends to a 1-morphism $\mathcal{S}\boxtimes\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$. In fact, $\mathcal{S}$ is a commutative monoid in the symmetric monoidal bicategory $\textsc{Pres}_{\mathbb{K}}$. Therefore, we may imagine $\mathcal{S}$ as a “categorified commutative algebra over $\mathbb{K}$”. We denote by $\textsc{Pres}_{\otimes,\mathbb{K}}$ the bicategory of symmetric monoidal locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear categories, where for two such objects $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ the category $\operatorname{\textsc{Hom}}_{\otimes,c,\mathbb{K}}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ consists of cocontinuous symmetric monoidal $\mathbb{K}$-linear functors and symmetric monoidal natural transformations. We will often simply write $\operatorname{\textsc{Hom}}_{\otimes}$ in place of $\operatorname{\textsc{Hom}}_{\otimes,c,\mathbb{K}}$, as $\mathbb{K}$ will often be implicit and we will never use non-cocontinuous symmetric monoidal functors. Let $\mathcal{S}\in\textsc{Pres}_{\otimes,\mathbb{K}}$. An $\mathcal{S}$-module in $\textsc{Pres}_{\mathbb{K}}$ is a locally presentable $\mathbb{K}$-linear category $\mathcal{C}$ together with an action $(-)\triangleright(-):\mathcal{S}\boxtimes\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ and unit and associativity data making the appropriate triangles and pentagons commute.
Definition 4.4. A module $V$ over a filtered limit $\widehat{A}=\varprojlim_{i}A_{i}$ of algebras is called discrete if for every $v\in V$ there is some $i\in\mathcal{I}$ for which $v$ is killed by $\ker(\widehat{A}\twoheadrightarrow A_{i})$.
Definition 2.2.1. Let $\mathcal{P}\mathrm{ic}(\mathcal{C})$ denote the $\infty$-groupoid (i.e. space) of invertible objects in $\mathcal{C}$ and equivalences between them. We will refer to this as the Picard $\infty$-groupoid of $\mathcal{C}$; it is a group-like $\mathbf{E}_{\infty}$-space, and thus the delooping of a connective Picard spectrum $\mathfrak{pic}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 2.1.6. Given an $\mathbf{E}_{\infty}$-ring $R$, we write $\mathrm{Pic}(R)$ for the Picard group $\mathrm{Pic}(\mathrm{Mod}(R))$.
Definition 2.1.1. The Picard group of $\mathcal{C}$ is the group of isomorphism classes of objects $x\in\mathcal{C}$ which are invertible, i.e. such that there exists an object $y\in\mathcal{C}$ such that $x\otimes y\simeq\mathbf{1}$. We will denote this group by $\mathrm{Pic}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 2. An $L_{\infty}$-superalgebra is a graded vector space $V$ equipped with a system $\{l_{k}|1\leq k<\infty\}$ of linear maps $l_{k}\colon V^{\otimes k}\rightarrow V$ with $\deg(l_{k})=k-2$ which are totally antisymmetric in the sense that $\displaystyle l_{k}(x_{\sigma(1)},\dots,x_{\sigma(k)})=\chi(\sigma)l_{k}(x_{1}% ,\dots,x_{n})$ for all $\sigma\in S_{n}$ and $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\in V,$ and, moreover, the following generalized form of the Jacobi identity holds for $0\leq n<\infty:$ $\displaystyle\displaystyle{\sum_{i+j=n+1}\sum_{\sigma\in S_{(i,n-i)}}\chi(% \sigma)(-1)^{i(j-1)}l_{j}(l_{i}(x_{\sigma(1)},\dots,x_{\sigma(i)}),x_{\sigma(i% +1)},\ldots,x_{\sigma(n)})=0,}$ where the inner summation is taken over all $(i,n-i)$-unshuffles with $i\geq 1.$
Definition 2. We define the operad $\mathcal{CM}^{\otimes}$ as (the nerve of) the 1-category in which • an object is a pair $(S,U)$ consisting of an object $S$ of $\mathcal{F}_{*}$ and a subset $U$ of $S^{o}$; • a morphism from $(S,U)$ to $(T,V)$ is a morphism $f:S\to T$ in $\mathcal{F}_{*}$ such that for each $v\in V$, the set $U\cap f^{-1}(v)$ has cardinality exactly $1$.
Definition 8. Let $\mathcal{F}^{+}$ be the category whose objects are pairs $(S,U)$, with $S$ a finite set and $U\subseteq S$ a subset, and in which a morphism from $(S,U)\to(T,V)$ is a morphism $f:S\to T$ of finite sets inducing a bijection $f|_{U}:U\cong V$. The disjoint union (which, mind you, is definitely not a coproduct) makes $\mathcal{F}^{+}$ into a symmetric monoidal category $(\mathcal{F}^{+})^{\amalg}$.
Definition 5.3. Given a diagram $S\xrightarrow{f}A\xleftarrow{g}T,$ with $f\in\mathcal{TP}^{N}$ and $g\in\mathcal{TP}^{R}$, let $f_{\otimes}^{*}T=\Big{\{}(s,t,\xi)\quad|\quad g(t)\mid f(s),\,\,s\textnormal{ % minimal, }t\textnormal{ maximal, }\xi\in C_{m}\Big{\}}.$ Here $m=\gcd\big{(}\frac{|f(s)|}{|s|},\frac{|g(t)|}{|t|}\big{)}$ as before, $s$ minimal means that there is no $s^{\prime}\mid s$ with $s^{\prime}\neq s$ and $g(t)\mid f(s^{\prime})$ (for $t$ fixed), and $t$ maximal means that there is no $t\mid t^{\prime}$ with $t\neq t^{\prime}$ and $g(t^{\prime})\mid f(s)$ (for $s$ fixed).
Definition 2.1. A truncation poset is a partially ordered set $S$ together with a function $|-|:S\to\mathbb{N}$ satisfying the following properties. (1) If $s\mid t$ then $|s|\mid|t|$. (2) If $s\mid t\mid u$ then $\frac{|u|}{|s|}=\frac{|u|}{|t|}\cdot\frac{|t|}{|s|}$. (3) If $d\mid|s|$ then there is a unique $t\in S$ with $t\mid s$ and $|t|=|s|/d$. In particular there is a unique $t\in S$ with $t\mid s$ and $|t|=1$. (4) If $s\in S$ and $d\in\mathbb{N}$ there is at most one $t\in S$ with $s\mid t$ and $|t|=d|s|$.
Definition 5.10. Suppose $f:S\to A$ is a $T$-map and $g:A\to T$ is an $N$-map. Then we declare the composite $g_{\otimes}\circ f_{\oplus}$ to be equal to the composite $t_{\oplus}\circ n_{\otimes}\circ r^{*}$, where the maps $t$, $n$ and $r$ are defined by the exponential diagram $\xymatrix{S\ar[d]_{f}&E\ar[l]_{-}r\ar[r]^{-}n&D\ar[d]^{t}\\ A\ar[rr]^{-}g&&T}$
Definition 3.11. Let $f:S\to T$ be an $N$-map. Then $f_{\otimes}:\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\to\mathbb{W}_{T}(k)$ is defined to be the unique map, functorial in $k$, such that the diagram $\xymatrix{\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w\ar[d]_{f_{\otimes}}&k^{S}\ar[d]^{f^{w}_% {\otimes}}\\ \mathbb{W}_{T}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w&k^{T}}$ commutes. Here $f^{w}_{\otimes}$ is the map defined by $(f^{w}_{\otimes}\langle x_{s}\rangle)_{t}=\prod_{s\in\widehat{f^{-1}}(t)}x_{s}% ^{|t|/|s|}.$
Definition 6.3. Let $\mathcal{TP}^{TNF}_{\langle n\rangle}$ be the subcategory of $\mathcal{TP}^{TNR}_{\textnormal{join}}$ whose objects are finite disjoint unions of $\langle m\rangle$ for $m\mid n$ and whose morphisms are given by equivalence classes of bispans $S\xleftarrow{f}A\xrightarrow{g}B\xrightarrow{h}T$ of such, with the following additional requirement: Suppose we decompose $A$ and $S$ as $\coprod A_{i}$ and $\coprod S_{j}$, respectively, and write $f$ as a coproduct of maps $A_{i}\xrightarrow{f_{i}}S_{j}\subset S$. If $A_{i}=\langle m_{i}\rangle$ and $S_{j}=\langle m_{j}\rangle$ then $m_{i}\mid m_{j}$ and $f_{i}$ is multiplication by $m_{j}/m_{i}$.
Definition 3.7. Let $f:S\to T$ be a $T$-map of truncation posets. Then $f_{\oplus}:\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\to\mathbb{W}_{T}(k)$ is defined to be the unique map, functorial in $k$, such that the diagram $\xymatrix{\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w\ar[d]_{f_{\oplus}}&k^{S}\ar[d]^{f^{w}_{% \oplus}}\\ \mathbb{W}_{T}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w&k^{T}}$ commutes. Here $f^{w}_{\oplus}$ is the map defined by $(f^{w}_{\oplus}\langle x_{s}\rangle)_{t}=\sum_{s\in f^{-1}(t)}\frac{|t|}{|s|}x% _{s}.$
Definition 5.5. We say a truncation poset $T$ has joins if $t\mid t_{1}$ and $t\mid t_{2}$ implies that there exists $t^{\prime}$ with $t_{1}\mid t^{\prime}$ and $t_{2}\mid t^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.17. A map $f:S\to T$ of truncation posets is a $T$-map ($T$ for transfer, not for the target of the map) if it satisfies the following additional conditions. (1) For every $s\in S$ and $t^{\prime}\in T$ with $f(s)\mid t^{\prime}$ there exists an $s^{\prime}\in S$ with $s\mid s^{\prime}$ and $f(s^{\prime})=t^{\prime}$. (2) For every $t\in T$ the set $f^{-1}(t)$ is finite. If $f$ satisfies the first condition (but not necessarily the second) we say that $f$ is a fibration.
Definition 4.2. Given a diagram $S\xrightarrow{f}A\xleftarrow{g}T$ with $f\in\mathcal{TP}^{T}$ and $g\in\mathcal{TP}^{R}$, we declare the composite $g^{*}\circ f_{\oplus}$ to be equal to the composite $f^{\prime}_{\oplus}\circ(g^{\prime})^{*}$, where $S\xleftarrow{g^{\prime}}f_{\oplus}^{*}T\xrightarrow{f^{\prime}}T$ and $f_{\oplus}^{*}T$ is defined by $f_{\oplus}^{*}T=\Big{\{}(s,t,\xi)\quad|\quad f(s)=g(t)\textnormal{ and }\xi\in C% _{m},\,\,m=\gcd\Big{(}\frac{|f(s)|}{|s|},\frac{|g(t)|}{|t|}\Big{)}\Big{\}}.$ Here $f^{\prime}:f_{\oplus}^{*}T\to T$ and $g^{\prime}:f_{\oplus}^{*}T\to S$ are the obvious maps, sending $(s,t,\xi)$ to $t$ and $s$, respectively. The norm on $f_{\oplus}^{*}T$ is defined by $|(s,t,\xi)|=\gcd(|s|,|t|),$ and we say $(s_{1},t_{1},\xi_{1})\mid(s_{2},t_{2},\xi_{2})$ if $s_{1}\mid s_{2}$, $t_{1}\mid t_{2}$, and $\xi_{1}=\xi_{2}$. Here we identify $C_{m_{1}}$ and $C_{m_{2}}$, using that $|f(s_{2})|/|s_{2}|=|f(s_{1})|/|s_{1}|$ and $|g(t_{2})|/|t_{2}|=|g(t_{1})|/|t_{1}|$.
Definition 2.12. A map $f:S\to T$ of truncation posets is a map of sets such that if $s_{1}\mid s_{2}$ then $f(s_{1})\mid f(s_{2})$ and $\frac{|f(s_{2})|}{|f(s_{1})|}=\frac{|s_{2}|}{|s_{1}|}$.
Definition 5.1. The category $\mathcal{TP}^{TNR}$ has objects the truncation posets, and a morphism $S\to T$ in $\mathcal{TP}^{TNR}$ is an equivalence class of diagrams $S\overset{f_{1}}{\longrightarrow}A_{1}\overset{f_{2}}{\longrightarrow}A_{2}% \overset{f_{3}}{\longrightarrow}\ldots\overset{f_{n}}{\longrightarrow}A_{n}% \overset{f_{n+1}}{\longrightarrow}T$ where each $f_{i}$ is a map in one of $\mathcal{TP}^{T}$, $\mathcal{TP}^{N}$ and $(\mathcal{TP}^{R})^{\mathrm{op}}$. The equivalence relation on such diagrams is generated by the following: (1) Isomorphism of diagrams. (2) Insertion of an identity morphism. (3) Composition if $f_{i}$ and $f_{i+1}$ are in the same category $\mathcal{TP}^{T}$, $\mathcal{TP}^{N}$ or $(\mathcal{TP}^{R})^{\mathrm{op}}$. (4) Commuting an $R$-map past a $T$-map as in Definition 4.2 above. (5) Commuting an $R$-map past an $N$-map as in Definition 5.7 below if the pullback $f_{\otimes}^{*}T$ exists as in Definition 5.4 below. (6) Commuting an $N$-map past a $T$-map as in Definition 5.10 below.
